sentences: Azita Youssefi (Persian: آزیتا یوسفی), born January 18, 1971 in St. Louis, Missouri, is an Iranian-American experimental musician, artist and music teacher based in Chicago.

She has been a voice and piano teacher at Chicago's Old Town School of Folk Music since 2002, and has served as composer and musical director for theater productions of musicals by Brian Torrey Scott.
Born in the United States to Iranian parents, Azita spent part of her childhood in Iran and was attending grade school in Tehran when the Iranian revolution began in late 1978.
As a teen, she would attend punk rock shows in Washington, D.C.  In 1989, Azita moved to Chicago to study at the Art Institute of Chicago.
In 1991, she formed the spastic noise-rock group The Scissor Girls with Sue Anne Zollinger on guitar (later replaced by Kelly Kuvo), Heather Melowic on drums, and herself on vocals and bass.
After two albums and a singles compilation, the Scissor Girls broke up in late 1996.
In late 1995, Azita played synthesizer for a short-lived Weasel Walter/Jim O'Rourke project Miss High-Heel.
Their self-titled CD was released on B-Sides Records (now NoSides Records) in 1998.
Their self-titled CD was released on B-Sides Records (now NoSides Records) in 1998.
Azita formed the Bride of No-No, another project known for extreme theatrics, in 1999.
After two albums the band eventually dissolved in 2002.
Music for Scattered Brains was originally released on vinyl in 1995.
In 1997, Azita returned to playing her childhood instrument, the piano while rooming with engineer Elliot Dicks who brought a piano into their loft.
Enantiodromia was released in 2003 on Drag City, and Life on the Fly followed in 2004.
Enantiodromia was released in 2003 on Drag City, and Life on the Fly followed in 2004.
Descriptions of this release varied, from comparisons with Steely Dan to comparisons with "a bad Rod Stewart album from the early 1980s".
Azita's album, How Will You?, was released on February 17, 2009.
Her latest album, Year was issued in November 2012.
